WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.080
J.J. articulated our mission so clearly and it's really meaningful for me to have this

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:17.559
codified now into the fiber of our organization and to be recognized as a B Corp.

00:00:17.559 --> 00:00:23.879
But what I really want to emphasize is that our contributions to the open source are funded

00:00:23.879 --> 00:00:28.920
by professional customers and their commitment to our professional tooling.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:34.439
So that's why the successes of our professional customers are so important.

00:00:34.439 --> 00:00:39.220
Their wins are all of our wins within the entire community.

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:44.400
So today I'm going to talk about ways that I've seen our professional customers overcome

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:50.840
common pain points that can trip up a team and limit their ability to become efficient

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:53.439
data-driven organizations.

00:00:53.439 --> 00:00:59.000
So a year ago I sat in this audience, like many of you maybe, as an engineer and a data

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.880
scientist working in industry.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:08.559
And I was trying to find out for my own how to make my analysis more powerful, more efficient,

00:01:08.559 --> 00:01:09.879
more impactful.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:12.160
And it's just funny how things turn out.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:17.160
Not too long after Conf, I had the opportunity to move to RStudio and now I'm working with

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:22.919
professional customers who are asking those same questions.

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:29.199
So in the time that I've been at RStudio, I've had a lot of customer conversations.

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:31.260
So far, well over 200.

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:34.839
Right now I'm averaging about 8 to 10 meetings a week.

00:01:34.839 --> 00:01:39.879
And our customers span across every industry that you can imagine.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:46.279
In my role, I get a unique insight into the various stages of a data science team's growth

00:01:46.279 --> 00:01:50.279
and their maturations and the challenges that they face.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:54.160
Sometimes that team I'm talking to is literally a team of one.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:57.959
And some of these teams are spanning the globe.

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:01.959
They have enterprise-level architectures and data products in place.

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:07.720
But I do see common elements among these teams and across all industries.

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:12.720
I've gotten a firsthand view into some of the successes that take a team from good to

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:13.720
great.

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:19.320
So I'm going to share two stories from teams that are at different maturity levels, but

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:25.880
they've succeeded in overcoming significant pain points.

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:32.759
So we can take broad strokes and talk about phases of maturity in a data science team.

00:02:32.759 --> 00:02:39.360
Now our first phase, right, these are our fun, excited newbie teams, right?

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:42.639
They're establishing buy-in for their analytics.

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:45.500
They're establishing credibility for what they're doing.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:52.100
Maybe they're coming off of Excel and spreadsheet-based things, but there's a lot of big and easy

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:57.460
wins for them as they start to explore what they can do with all the capabilities of working

00:02:57.460 --> 00:03:00.220
in a codified analytics means.

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:02.100
So this group I love.

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:07.779
They're just dazzled by all the amazing things that they can do with code.

00:03:07.779 --> 00:03:12.699
Our phase two teams are a little further along in the path, right?

00:03:12.699 --> 00:03:17.740
At this point, they've established buy-in, they've got credibility.

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:19.380
Often they're growing in size.

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:20.899
They've got more people on the team.

00:03:20.899 --> 00:03:24.500
Maybe they're adding more data products to their portfolio.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:29.259
But definitely no matter what's going on, their data products have been recognized as

00:03:29.259 --> 00:03:31.419
being more business critical, right?

00:03:31.419 --> 00:03:34.000
They've got cred behind what they're doing.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:40.100
And that's great, but along with that comes greater expectations and more demand.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:45.220
And so now these teams are in this state of figuring out, what the hell have we done?

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:47.020
And how are we going to keep this up?

00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:49.699
We're not sure what we've gotten ourselves into.

00:03:49.699 --> 00:03:54.179
And there's a lot of growing pains associated with the phase two teams.

00:03:54.179 --> 00:03:58.619
And then lastly, there's that upper echelon phase three team, right?

00:03:58.619 --> 00:04:01.539
They are hitting on all cylinders.

00:04:01.539 --> 00:04:03.619
They've got it all figured out.

00:04:03.619 --> 00:04:09.860
And I think there's definitely an asthmatotic path that phase two teams take towards becoming

00:04:09.899 --> 00:04:10.899
a phase three.

00:04:10.899 --> 00:04:16.019
But really, no one actually gets it all figured out in the end.

00:04:16.019 --> 00:04:20.619
So the two teams I'm going to talk about today, team one is a phase one team.

00:04:20.619 --> 00:04:22.820
They're moving from an Excel world.

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:25.940
They've got really inefficient reporting, emailing things around.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:28.739
But they've discovered Shiny.

00:04:28.739 --> 00:04:33.459
And so they're enthusiastic about this, but they're really struggling to figure out how

00:04:33.459 --> 00:04:37.980
to get their data products into their consumers' hands from here.

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:40.820
Team two is going to be a phase two team.

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:46.059
And they're trying to maintain an efficient workflow as they grow.

00:04:46.059 --> 00:04:52.100
But they're finding some issues because they're becoming a little too cavalier in their approach.

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:57.940
So when teams are tangled up looking for answers to these types of questions, it can take weeks

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:02.260
or months or sometimes years to overcome these issues.

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:06.260
You get the benefit of 20-20 hindsight and reflection.

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:10.940
And you can see these struggles and have visibility of their success strategies.

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:16.380
I want you to walk away from this talk with enough information and vision that you can

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:19.700
see that there's a forward path for your own team.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:24.320
And I invite you to come to the lounge at some point this week and have a deeper and

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:31.059
more specific conversation about how to move your own team to the next level.

00:05:31.059 --> 00:05:34.619
Since we're talking professional customers, we need to have a quick orientation on our

00:05:34.779 --> 00:05:36.779
RStudio professional products.

00:05:36.779 --> 00:05:40.100
So RStudio offers three professional products.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:44.820
RStudio Server Pro, Connect, and Package Manager.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:51.100
These products provide a modular platform, which provide the shortest and the most efficient

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:56.140
path for lasting value in a data science team for all entities.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:06:02.739
So RStudio Server Pro is your place for R and Python data analysis, now supporting Jupyter

00:06:02.739 --> 00:06:07.579
sessions as well as the traditional RStudio session.

00:06:07.579 --> 00:06:09.799
Connect is a publication platform.

00:06:09.799 --> 00:06:14.380
And this is where all the data products that are created go to live, where stakeholders

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:18.339
can consume and interact with those data products.

00:06:18.339 --> 00:06:23.820
And RStudio Package Manager provides a managed and controlled environment for your packages.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:31.420
But at the core of this are the open source packages that we're dedicated to.

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:33.739
Now let me introduce you to our phase one team.

00:06:33.739 --> 00:06:38.100
So they had a handful of analyses all tied up in Excel files.

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:39.420
They used to email them around.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:42.260
It bogged things down tremendously.

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:49.980
But they've discovered Shiny, and they have jumped wholeheartedly on board.

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:54.859
But the biggest issue facing this team is now needing a way to get their Shiny app into

00:06:54.859 --> 00:06:57.980
the hands of their stakeholders so it could be used.

00:06:58.019 --> 00:07:03.980
So for a little while, they were simply publishing to local hosts, and it quickly became apparent

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:08.420
that that was not a stable or scalable solution.

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:13.420
But they also weren't sure if they were going to need to be reliant on an outside group

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:16.299
to be able to help get their apps published.

00:07:16.299 --> 00:07:24.700
So for them, a win is being able to have their work visible and discoverable by their stakeholders.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:29.519
And really, success in this realm would open up the door for this group to be able to reach

00:07:29.519 --> 00:07:34.220
their broader goals of securing buy-in for what they're doing so they can expand their

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:36.459
scope and their impact in the organization.

00:07:36.459 --> 00:07:43.500
They can get off of this repetitive just updating the same quarterly report every quarter and

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:49.579
get into more forward thinking and proactive analysis.

00:07:49.579 --> 00:07:56.299
So my phase one team found that RStudio Connect provided the best home for their data products.

00:07:56.299 --> 00:08:00.140
What was really appealing to them was the ease of deployment.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:04.500
So Connect permits push button deployment from the IDE, right from this little blue

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.980
button that's really small on your screen here.

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:13.700
But what you do, you push this button, and all of your packages and your R version information

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:19.739
is bundled up behind the scenes, shipped off to the Connect server, and unpacked.

00:08:19.739 --> 00:08:27.260
And so deployment is easy as pushing a button, and two minutes later, you're off and running.

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:31.660
Now once this Team Shiny app was available on Connect, stakeholders could interact with

00:08:31.660 --> 00:08:37.020
all this information in a self-service manner, and it didn't require these iterations, going

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:40.539
back to the data scientists time and time again whenever they wanted to see a different

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:44.859
view or a different variable.

00:08:44.859 --> 00:08:50.619
But what was really great to see with this team was that they really began to leverage

00:08:50.619 --> 00:08:54.140
the multiple data types supported by Connect.

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:58.260
So for them, Connect opened the door to new gains for them.

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:03.940
So in addition to this original Shiny app, they discovered they could tackle all sorts

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:07.539
of other inefficiencies in their processes.

00:09:07.539 --> 00:09:13.219
They're using scheduled and ad hoc reporting in R Markdown and using Jupyter Notebooks,

00:09:13.219 --> 00:09:18.739
sending customized emails, using pins as part of an ETL process.

00:09:18.739 --> 00:09:23.739
So I want to show what this would look like as an example.

00:09:23.739 --> 00:09:28.859
So in Connect for report scheduling, when you upload and you're working with an R Markdown

00:09:28.859 --> 00:09:35.780
document or a Jupyter Notebook, you have the ability to specify both the report frequency

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:38.820
and the audience for which you want to send that report to.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:44.500
And it can be stored just on the Connect server, or it can be emailed out automatically.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:49.419
Now this team's also integrated in condition-based triggers.

00:09:49.419 --> 00:09:56.059
So on some reports, it'll only send an email out if a certain criteria is met, say if it's

00:09:56.059 --> 00:10:05.979
a low inventory condition or if there's performance threshold criteria that are being exceeded.

00:10:05.979 --> 00:10:11.099
Another workflow they've fully taken advantage of is using scheduled R Markdowns to write

00:10:11.099 --> 00:10:13.260
ETL data to a pen.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:17.979
And so this data lives right in Connect, and it's accessed by their scripts.

00:10:17.979 --> 00:10:22.380
They can control who has access to this data on the pen.

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:27.020
And because it's ephemeral data, it didn't really make a lot of sense to take this little

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:29.580
chunk of data and put it into a database.

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:33.099
But they didn't want to be saving and importing CSV files.

00:10:33.099 --> 00:10:37.119
And so for them, a pen was a perfect solution.

00:10:37.119 --> 00:10:41.940
This data is then accessed by their Shiny app, and now they have a regular update cycle

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:47.940
behind their main data product, so the information is always fresh and relevant.

00:10:47.940 --> 00:10:54.900
So my team 1 channeled their enthusiasm of moving to a codified solution, and they found

00:10:54.900 --> 00:11:00.320
tremendous efficiency gains in value add by getting their workflow streamlined and their

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:05.900
products right into the hands of their customers.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:07.700
Now it's time to meet our phase 2 team.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:10.099
So this is a fun bunch.

00:11:10.099 --> 00:11:12.280
They've grown in their data offerings.

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:16.619
They've established credibility in the organization for what they do.

00:11:16.619 --> 00:11:21.580
But they're in an awkward spot, because as their data products are becoming more business

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:27.940
critical, they're finding that their phase 1 days of doing things is not sustainable.

00:11:27.940 --> 00:11:32.700
They've been burned a few times by pushing things straight into production, and things

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:34.659
have gone awry.

00:11:34.659 --> 00:11:39.859
They know that they need to start adopting more process rigor, being more diligent about

00:11:39.859 --> 00:11:40.859
version control.

00:11:40.859 --> 00:11:47.219
But right now it's just hard to let go of those freewheeling days of phase 1, and it

00:11:47.219 --> 00:11:55.859
just seems like a jumble of pieces that don't have a clear order where they need to fall.

00:11:55.859 --> 00:12:01.900
This team's biggest challenges include tool and process-based issues, but a big part of

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:05.119
it is also philosophy.

00:12:05.119 --> 00:12:09.059
Because of the high visibility of the past fumbles that they had in pushing straight

00:12:09.140 --> 00:12:14.900
to production, they're now butting heads with IT over deployment strategies.

00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:20.140
So IT was really uneasy with the push button deployment feature of Connect.

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:25.299
It was a little too easy to send things out to production.

00:12:25.299 --> 00:12:31.440
That was what made Connect such a great sell in the phase 1 days, but now it's the source

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.179
of friction.

00:12:33.179 --> 00:12:39.780
So in this case, IT put out a nine-page list of instructions to follow in order to deploy

00:12:39.780 --> 00:12:46.099
to production, and they figured, hey, if anyone's diligent enough to go through all nine pages,

00:12:46.099 --> 00:12:50.419
they'd pass their test and they could be trusted to publish.

00:12:50.419 --> 00:12:54.659
Clearly this did not go well with the data scientist team, and they just felt this overall

00:12:54.659 --> 00:13:01.419
turmoil of what have we done and how are we going to keep this thing going?

00:13:01.419 --> 00:13:06.460
Questions between the data scientists and IT felt like data scientists are from Mars

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:08.739
and IT is from Venus.

00:13:08.739 --> 00:13:14.099
Words like Jenkins and DevOps were swirling around in their heads, and it was just overwhelming

00:13:14.099 --> 00:13:15.820
for them.

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:24.119
So a win for this team is to establish a managed deployment workflow that was still efficient,

00:13:24.119 --> 00:13:29.380
but it was respectful and cognizant of a more formalized understanding of what production

00:13:29.380 --> 00:13:31.159
means.

00:13:31.159 --> 00:13:36.479
And if they can be successful in this realm, this helps them achieve higher goals, building

00:13:36.479 --> 00:13:42.200
a foundation of best practices and a collaborative relationship with their IT team.

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:47.200
But I want to tease out a little bit on this philosophy issue that really feeds into phase

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:50.400
2's team points.

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.559
So what is production?

00:13:52.559 --> 00:13:57.239
It can kind of feel like that summer family road trip of, like, are we there yet?

00:13:57.239 --> 00:13:58.239
Where are we going?

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.880
Frankly, how do you know when you're actually there?

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:08.520
So right now you might be having a hard time formalizing what it means to be in production.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:13.359
And if this idea of production sounds kind of nebulous, you're not alone.

00:14:13.359 --> 00:14:19.159
Look around, and if you know clearly in your head what production means, raise your hand.

00:14:19.159 --> 00:14:22.000
It's a quiet audience right now.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.239
Guaranteed, if you ask 10 different groups what production and production readiness means

00:14:27.239 --> 00:14:32.640
to them, you're going to get 10 different answers.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:36.320
So let's talk about what production might mean.

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:42.760
An incomplete concept of production only considers that the data product is accurate and it's

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:47.460
ready to be used for informing business decisions.

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:51.859
So this is where my phase 2 team got bit.

00:14:51.859 --> 00:14:56.179
They made the mistake of saying, it works fine on my desktop, it's ready to go.

00:14:56.179 --> 00:14:59.900
And if that doesn't get your spidey senses all tingly, what if I tell you it was a Friday

00:14:59.900 --> 00:15:02.219
afternoon when they said that?

00:15:02.219 --> 00:15:06.739
And it was right before an organizational deadline.

00:15:06.739 --> 00:15:11.780
So in my customer conversations, I've seen a number of in-house solutions, yet no one

00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:15.020
really knows what it means to be in production.

00:15:15.020 --> 00:15:21.340
And then as demand for products grow, it becomes increasingly important and painful to address

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:24.979
scaling and security, stability, availability.

00:15:24.979 --> 00:15:30.900
These in-house solutions tend to crumble as higher demand is placed on them.

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:35.340
So a more formally defined state of production not only ensures that the data product is

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:41.219
correct, but it's in a stable environment, it's safe, it's secure, and it scales and

00:15:41.219 --> 00:15:43.299
responds appropriately.

00:15:43.299 --> 00:15:44.900
These are the infrastructure things.

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:49.859
But there's also a state of mind associated with production, and this is important.

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:54.940
In production, you're thinking ahead and expecting that every change you make has the

00:15:54.940 --> 00:15:56.580
potential to disrupt.

00:15:56.580 --> 00:16:03.140
So you're designing, you're testing, and you're architecting to prevent that.

00:16:03.140 --> 00:16:07.380
Now my phase two team, they were already working with RStudio Connect, and they saw how this

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:12.539
could provide that stable, secure, scalable wear for production.

00:16:12.539 --> 00:16:17.780
We've got built-in authentication, access management, app-by-app performance tuning.

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:21.059
They're also able to stand up a staging environment on QA, which was great.

00:16:21.059 --> 00:16:25.460
But taking advantage of these infrastructure controls was one thing.

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:29.820
But the transformation happened as the team cultivated their production readiness mindset

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:35.619
and incorporated best practices with version control all in line in an automated DevTest

00:16:35.619 --> 00:16:37.659
prod workflow.

00:16:37.659 --> 00:16:38.700
And that was a mouthful.

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:42.219
So I want to illustrate what this workflow looks like, because it's very versatile and

00:16:42.219 --> 00:16:45.900
it's useful for many teams.

00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:51.260
So what this means, team two has linked their master repo in GitHub to the production instance

00:16:51.260 --> 00:16:52.580
of Connect.

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:57.500
And Connect is automatically watching that repo and updating it if changes occur.

00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:02.700
However, all development feature additions and whatnot are worked off a branch to that

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:03.859
master.

00:17:03.859 --> 00:17:07.540
So the branch repository is deployed to a staging environment.

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:12.219
And this way, the data scientists can still see and touch and feel and play with their

00:17:12.219 --> 00:17:17.579
deployed content without disruption to the production instance.

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:21.699
When this content in the branch is approved and ready to be moved to production, a pull

00:17:21.699 --> 00:17:24.420
request is made to merge the master.

00:17:24.420 --> 00:17:28.380
And Connect automatically redeploys the updated version.

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:33.140
So this automated DevTest prod workflow met the data scientists' needs for an efficient

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:34.300
workflow.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:41.859
And it met the requirements of IT for a managed strategy that allowed QA in a production mindset.

00:17:41.859 --> 00:17:49.060
This philosophy change and automated workflow has been a tremendous value add for team two.

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:52.420
I've got a quick illustration of it.

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:53.819
Just to show what it looks like in Connect.

00:17:53.819 --> 00:17:56.660
There was a lot of clicking, so I didn't feel like I could show it live today.

00:17:56.660 --> 00:18:00.339
But you can see there's multiple versions of an app, of a version.

00:18:00.339 --> 00:18:10.099
And so in GitHub, we switch to the development branch for the asset and initiate a pull request.

00:18:10.099 --> 00:18:18.979
When the merge request is approved, then we move to Connect.

00:18:18.979 --> 00:18:27.140
And I know that this content is Git-backed, because in the info panel on Connect, it will

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:30.979
show me the branch or the repository that it's watching.

00:18:30.979 --> 00:18:33.339
And it will periodically check for updates.

00:18:33.339 --> 00:18:36.979
Or in this case, I can force an update, because I know that there's changes coming.

00:18:36.979 --> 00:18:38.420
So Git sees those changes.

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:43.219
And Connect sees those changes and redeploys.

00:18:43.219 --> 00:18:46.260
And so now we can see that the changes that we made in production that were approved are

00:18:46.260 --> 00:18:50.459
now available and ready for us in production.

00:18:50.459 --> 00:18:52.939
Okay.

00:18:52.939 --> 00:18:55.319
Close things up here.

00:18:55.319 --> 00:18:57.260
So I want to close with a few thoughts.

00:18:57.260 --> 00:19:01.500
I do not want imposter syndrome to get you.

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:05.699
There are plenty of sexy and intimidating words out there when we talk data science

00:19:05.699 --> 00:19:10.900
in the enterprise, Hadoop and Docker, Kubernetes, Spark and Slurm.

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:12.060
It's okay.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:16.280
You don't have to know or understand it all.

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:19.780
Because successful enterprise data analytics teams are just that.

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:20.979
They're a team.

00:19:20.979 --> 00:19:23.060
So you do what you do best.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:28.020
But build up, count on, communicate, and learn with your team.

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:34.880
You need an R admin, you need IT and DevOps, and you need to be listening to your stakeholders.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:38.359
So to recap, what I want you to see today is you can have your own success story, and

00:19:38.359 --> 00:19:42.599
I want you to benefit from seeing some solutions and common pain points that might confront

00:19:42.599 --> 00:19:44.119
you along the way.

00:19:44.119 --> 00:19:47.479
It's important that you find an efficient way to share your data products.

00:19:47.479 --> 00:19:48.479
Work smart.

00:19:48.479 --> 00:19:51.880
Use automation and reproducibility to make efficient workflows.

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:56.699
And know where you're going on this journey to production and bring the whole team along.

00:19:56.699 --> 00:20:00.920
And above all, I want you to think forward and ask questions and come visit us at the

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:03.719
lounge for a more detailed conversation.

00:20:03.719 --> 00:20:06.719
Thank you, Katie.

00:20:06.719 --> 00:20:18.319
So I forgot to mention, if you have any questions, the best way to ask them is just to go to

00:20:18.319 --> 00:20:23.000
sly.do, and we're in track number three, Imperial Room.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:31.479
So I think we just have time for one question before the next speaker.

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:35.359
So there's a couple questions that came in, but one of them was, so what do you think

00:20:35.359 --> 00:20:40.680
are some ways that data science teams can accelerate their learning and especially adopt

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:48.199
newer open source packages they may not have used before, like Plumber or TensorFlow?

00:20:48.199 --> 00:20:53.079
I really enjoy, it sounds so fundamental, but I find that the best learning happens

00:20:53.079 --> 00:20:59.000
when folks go to the main landing pages for each of these packages.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.359
So people may not realize, but the homepage for Shiny, for R Markdown, there's a getting

00:21:03.359 --> 00:21:07.959
started section there with tremendous tutorials.

00:21:07.959 --> 00:21:12.359
I'll say my first Shiny app I built by copying and pasting code from Stack Overflow, probably

00:21:12.359 --> 00:21:14.400
like maybe your first Shiny app.

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:20.160
And after watching the tutorials on just one tutorial from the Shiny page, I started

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:24.479
a Shiny app from blank page, and I knew every element and where it needed to go.

00:21:24.479 --> 00:21:27.319
So I think the resources are out there.

00:21:27.319 --> 00:21:30.959
And fundamentally, a lot of the building blocks of knowledge that people can benefit from

00:21:30.959 --> 00:21:32.959
are right on those main pages for the packages.

00:21:32.959 --> 00:21:33.959
Awesome.

00:21:33.959 --> 00:21:33.959


